<div id="review_4118972281" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4118972281" />
    <a title="Kai Bythesea" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/137677935-kai-bythesea"><img alt="Kai Bythesea" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4118972281?book_show_action=true">Jul 17, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kai Bythesea" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kai Bythesea" href="/user/show/137677935-kai-bythesea">Kai Bythesea</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4118972281" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11629410334779020035">Bernard Pomerance wrote <i>The Elephant Man</i> in 1979. However, it is an historical drama set in Victorian London and based on true accounts of Joseph Carey Merrick’s life. Dr. Richard Treves who was Merrick’s physician at the London Hospital released his own book in 1923, and Ashley Montagu wrote about Merrick in a book released in 1971. Pomerance uses these accounts as the foundation for his dramatic work. <br/><br/>The play explores many subjects, but at its core, it looks at how a disfigured man may provid</span>
  <span id="freeText11629410334779020035" style="display:none">Bernard Pomerance wrote <i>The Elephant Man</i> in 1979. However, it is an historical drama set in Victorian London and based on true accounts of Joseph Carey Merrick’s life. Dr. Richard Treves who was Merrick’s physician at the London Hospital released his own book in 1923, and Ashley Montagu wrote about Merrick in a book released in 1971. Pomerance uses these accounts as the foundation for his dramatic work. <br /><br />The play explores many subjects, but at its core, it looks at how a disfigured man may provide for himself financially and gain acceptance in society. The play begins with the dichotomy of the monstrous, freak-show performer who is Merrick versus the educated, refined, moralistic, Dr. Treves. One may all too readily assume that Merrick’s salvation is Dr. Treves and the London Hospital but the play challenges this assumption. Pomerance mercilessly critiques Victorian English ideals of benevolence, reformation, charity, morality, and sexuality. The play ends on a decidedly sad note and the question that lingers for readers is – what does normality actually look like, and more crucially, what is the cost of becoming normal? <br /><br />For a more extensive review, please see my blog post - <a href="https://whyreadplays.com/2020/10/18/example-post/" rel="nofollow noopener">my link text</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="11629410334779020035" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


